## NAMING RULES (ENFORCED)

When generating new error codes:

1. Identify the domain. Use only registered namespaces:
   AUTH | USER | ACCOUNT | PAYMENT | MEDIA | COURSE | NOTIFICATION |
   VALIDATION | RATE_LIMIT | PERMISSION | INTEGRATION | INTERNAL

2. Name the condition in UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (no namespace prefix in the name part)
   - Conditions ending in state: NOT_FOUND, ALREADY_EXISTS, EXPIRED, REVOKED, SUSPENDED
   - Conditions describing action failure: FAILED, REJECTED, DECLINED
   - Conditions describing input: MISSING_FIELD, INVALID_FORMAT, OUT_OF_RANGE

3. Combine: DOMAIN__CONDITION
   USER__NOT_FOUND ✅
   PAYMENT__CARD_DECLINED ✅
   VALIDATION__MISSING_FIELD ✅

4. Before creating a new code: search `errors/catalog.py` for semantically equivalent codes.
   If an existing code covers the situation — use it. No duplicates.

---

## BEFORE CREATING A NEW CODE — CHECKLIST

Ask these questions in order:

- [ ] Does an existing code in `errors/catalog.py` already describe this condition?
- [ ] Is there a generic code that applies (e.g., `VALIDATION__FAILED`) I should use instead?
- [ ] Is this code reusable across multiple endpoints, or hyper-specific to one call?
- [ ] Have I chosen the right namespace from the registered list?
- [ ] Is the name free of `_ERROR`, `_FAILURE`, `_EXCEPTION` suffixes?
- [ ] Is the HTTP status code consistent with the catalog entry?

Only after all checks pass: add the code to `errors/catalog.py` with `description`, `http_status`, and `since_version`.

---

## AUTO-REWRITE RULES (Pattern Recognition)

When reviewing code, apply these automatic transformations:

| Detected pattern in response | Auto-convert to |
|-------------------------------|-----------------|
| `"not found"` / `"does not exist"` | `{DOMAIN}__NOT_FOUND` |
| `"already exists"` / `"duplicate"` / `"taken"` | `{DOMAIN}__ALREADY_EXISTS` or `VALIDATION__DUPLICATE_VALUE` |
| `"invalid"` + credentials/password/token | `AUTH__INVALID_CREDENTIALS` or `AUTH__TOKEN_MALFORMED` |
| `"expired"` + token/session | `AUTH__TOKEN_EXPIRED` or `AUTH__SESSION_EXPIRED` |
| `"permission"` / `"not allowed"` / `"forbidden"` | `PERMISSION__DENIED` |
| `"required"` / `"missing"` + field | `VALIDATION__MISSING_FIELD` |
| `"invalid format"` / `"invalid email"` / `"must be"` | `VALIDATION__INVALID_FORMAT` |
| `"too long"` / `"max length"` | `VALIDATION__TOO_LONG` |
| `"too short"` / `"min length"` | `VALIDATION__TOO_SHORT` |
| `"rate limit"` / `"too many requests"` | `RATE_LIMIT__EXCEEDED` |
| `"unauthorized"` (no auth) | `AUTH__UNAUTHENTICATED` |
| `"unauthorized"` (has auth, no permission) | `AUTH__UNAUTHORIZED` or `PERMISSION__DENIED` |
| `"server error"` / `"something went wrong"` | `INTERNAL__ERROR` |
| `"unavailable"` / `"maintenance"` | `INTERNAL__SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE` |
| `"insufficient funds"` / `"payment failed"` | `PAYMENT__INSUFFICIENT_FUNDS` / `PAYMENT__FAILED` |

---

## DOMAIN INFERENCE GUIDE

When code context is ambiguous, infer the domain:

- File is in `auth/`, `authentication/`, token views → `AUTH__`
- File operates on User model → `USER__`
- File is a serializer or form → `VALIDATION__`
- File handles Stripe/payments → `PAYMENT__`
- File handles file upload → `MEDIA__`
- File is a catch-all / middleware / handler → `INTERNAL__`
- File gates features or roles → `PERMISSION__`
- File calls external APIs → `INTEGRATION__`

---

## RESPONSE STRUCTURE SCHEMA (never deviate)

```typescript
// Success
{
  success: true,
  data: object | array | null,
  meta: { request_id: string, version: string }
}

// Single Error
{
  success: false,
  error: {
    code: string,              // DOMAIN__CONDITION — REQUIRED
    details?: object           // machine-readable context only — OPTIONAL
  },
  meta: { request_id: string, version: string }
}

// Multi Error (validation)
{
  success: false,
  errors: Array<{
    code: string,
    details?: object
  }>,
  meta: { request_id: string, version: string }
}
```

Fields `error.message`, `error.description`, `error.text` are BANNED from all response bodies.
